condition.narrative:
[Extract from Section 5 of the Letter of Arrangement between AgDevCo and the PIDG Trust dated 25 July 2013]
The Recipient confirms that it will:

(a)	procure that the Project will be carried out in countries and territories eligible to receive official development assistance as set out in the OECD’s DAC List of ODA Recipients as amended from time to time; 
(c)	conduct its business with reasonable skill and care and in accordance with internationally recognised financial and business practices;
(d)		maintain at all times a firm of independent accountants acceptable to the PIDG Trust as auditors; 
(e)	comply with its reporting obligations to the PIDG Trust set out herein; 
(f)	obtain and maintain all insurances as shall be usual for a business undertaking the activities undertaken by the Recipient (including as to levels of cover), including but not limited to: (i) fire (or all risks) on assets, as applicable; and (ii) directors’ and officers’ liability;
(g)	conduct its business in compliance with OECD Principles of Corporate Governance issued from time to time to the extent applicable for the Recipient;  
(h)	procure that the audited financial statements it produces in respect of each accounting period are prepared in accordance with approved accounting principles; and
(j)	in accordance with the code of conduct and operating policies and procedures of the PIDG, institute internal procedures and controls for the purpose of preventing the Recipient from becoming an instrument for money laundering, the financing of terrorist activities, fraud or other corrupt or illegal purposes or practices.

5.2	The Recipient undertakes to supply all assistance to the PMU and the PIDG Trust, either as specified in this Letter of Arrangement and the Proposal or as reasonably requested, and shall co-operate with the PMU and the PIDG Trust in monitoring and evaluating the Project, including ensuring access to the Project sites as required by the PMU and the PIDG Trust. 

5.3	The Recipient will prepare and submit to the PMU on behalf of the PIDG Trust the following documents:

(b)	at least 20 days before the start of the Recipient’s accounting period, a copy of the Recipient’s business or annual operating plan and budget for such accounting period;

(c)	within 30 days of the end of each quarter (31 March, 30 June, 30 September, 31 December), unaudited financial statements for the Recipient or any other form of financial statement satisfactory to the Recipient’s PIDG Donors and the PMU (the PMU being responsible for seeking Recipient’s PIDG Donors’ approval).including the following information:

•	a forecast cash flow, which will include the following information
-	any projects/investments in the Recipient’s project pipeline (including a table with breakdown of costs per project and supporting narrative on each investment/project);
-	the Recipient’s operating costs, including funding required for any due diligence requirements;
-	any pre-project pipeline amount requested; 
-	funding expected from any other source and how this will be used to support the Recipient’s operations;

•	the Recipient’s balance sheet and profit and loss (analysed by month / quarter); and
•	the assumptions and risks behind the information provided.

•	a statement confirming whether/when the next disbursement from the Grant is expected to be required with some narrative to justify the timing and amount requested;

(d)	within 30 days of the end of each quarter  progress reports on the status of the activities of the Recipient including any special reports relating to the Project in such form and detail as any member of the PIDG may require;

(e)	a material risk report for the Recipient;

(f)	within one hundred and fifty (150) days after the end of the first accounting period of the Recipient, and within one hundred and twenty (120) days thereafter, a copy of the Recipient’s audited financial statements for such accounting period prepared in accordance with International Financial Reporting Standards (www.ifrs.com) together with an audit report thereon signed by the Recipient’s auditors, which shall include an annual management assertion of the satisfactory financial procedures and controls used by the Recipient;

(g)	logframes and reports on the development impact of the Project in accordance with the methodology and format agreed by the members of the PIDG and set out in the “PIDG Results Monitoring Handbook” as may be amended from time to time;

(h)	case studies relating to the Project in such form and substance as the PIDG Trust may reasonably require from time to time; 

(i)	prompt notice of any proposed change in the purpose, nature or scope of the business or operations of the Recipient; 

(j)	at least fourteen (14) days' notice of the calling of any meeting of the Recipient’s shareholders indicating the agenda thereof, and as soon as available thereafter the minutes of such meeting;

(k)	prompt notice of any litigation which is reasonably likely to affect, materially and adversely, the Recipient or the members of the PIDG;

(l)	without limitation to the above, any information reasonably requested by the PIDG Trust (and it will and allow representatives of the PIDG Trust and the members of the PIDG the right to review the progress of any investment by the Recipient and allow the representatives of the PIDG Trust and the Recipient the right to audit the books and records of the Recipient provided that the Recipient shall not be obliged to disclose any information which is subject to confidentiality or non-disclosure undertakings in favour of a third party);

(m)	such reasonable support and assistance as the Recipient may require when undertaking any mid-term or progress review of the Recipient; and

(n)	a final report and consolidated financial statement on termination of this Letter of Arrangement in a form to be agreed with the PMU.

5.4	The Recipient agrees (i) to retain or cause to be retained for at least seven (7) years, all records (contracts, orders, invoices, bills, receipts and other documents) evidencing the Recipient’s expenditure and ensure that such records and accounts are included in the annual audit of the Recipient and enable the members of the PIDG’s representatives to examine such records and accounts of the Recipient; and (ii) without limitation to the above, to furnish or cause to be furnished to the members of the PIDG any information reasonably requested by a member of the PIDG and to allow representatives of the members of the PIDG on reasonable notice the right to review the progress of the Project. 

5.5	If at any stage the Recipient should become aware of, or suspect, any misappropriation or diversion of funds or possible fraud or corruption relating to the Project, the Recipient must report the matter immediately in accordance with the PIDG’s anticorruption and integrity policy and procedures as may be amended from time to time.

5.6	The Recipient agrees that until the Grant has been fully spent it will not, without the prior consent of the PMU on behalf of the PIDG Trust, pay or transfer any of its income, directly or indirectly by way of dividend or bonus or otherwise by way of profit to any shareholder of the Recipient, and on its dissolution the shareholders of the Recipient will, following consultation in good faith with the PMU, transfer or apply the assets of the Recipient solely to another not for profit organisation with similar purposes, and that has the capacity to comply with the requirements set out in this Letter of Arrangement. 

5.7	The PIDG Trust agrees that the Recipient may remunerate its staff as it considers reasonable and appropriate, unless and until it becomes a PIDG facility. This may include an incentive-based arrangement that rewards staff for delivery of certain objectives. 

5.8	Even though the Recipient is not a PIDG facility, the Recipient and the PIDG Trust agree to disclose such information relating to the Grant as is required to meet the requirements of the PIDG’s disclosure policy and procedures as may be amended from to time.
